{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488495"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:44:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:44:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"461"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/461"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.09,0.04,0.12,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111817"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/461"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93887"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31877"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34251"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111817"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA fit 43-year-old woman presents for a routine check and enquires about various screening protocols. She is asymptomatic, does not smoke or take any medications. She does not have any apparent relevant medical history, but does have a family history of a number of diseases. Her mother developed breast cancer at the age of 76, her paternal grandfather bowel cancer at the age of 74, her brother developed type II diabetes at the age of 60 and her paternal aunt carcinoma of the ovary at the age of 65. Her BMI is 24 and the physical examination is unremarkable. She is concerned that she might be at risk and should be screened.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice to give the patient with regard to screening at this stage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["5 yearly cervical screening test","2 yearly faecal occult blood test","Annual glucose tolerance test","Annual mammography","3 yearly colonoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOf all the conditions listed, the one the patient is most at risk from at her current age is a gynaecological malignancy and she should be encouraged to have a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical screening test\u003C/strong\u003E. The cervical screening test has changed in recent years to a human papilloma virus (HPV) based test and the frequency of screening has changed from two yearly to five yearly (unless abnormalities are detected on the test).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is in the average risk category for carcinoma of the colon and does not need screening for this disease until she reaches the age of 45. She does not appear to have any personal risk factors for diabetes and the need for screening for this condition is less urgent that that for gynaecological cancer. She definitely would not qualify for an annual glucose tolerance test but may benefit from having her diabetes risk calculated on a three yearly basis with the Australian type 2 diabetes assessment tool (AUSDRISK).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is at increased risk of carcinoma of the breast, but does not need mammographic screening until she reaches the age of 50. For asymptomatic, low-risk women, BreastScreen Australia recommends mammography screening every two years for women aged 50\u201374 years.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical screening is of proven benefit in risk reduction for cervical cancer."],"references":["National Cervical Screening Program. Quick Reference Guide: Clinician Collected Cervical Screening Tests. Australian Department of Health [internet]; published Oct 2016 [cited 2021 Feb 09]. Available from: https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/national-cervical-screening-program-quick-reference-guide-clinician-collected-cervical-screening-tests","Royal Australian College of General Practitioners and Diabetes Australia [Internet]. Melbourne Victoria: RACGP 2020. Management of type 2 diabetes: a handbook for general practice; [updated 2020 Nov 1; cited 2021 feb 09]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/41fee8dc-7f97-4f87-9d90-b7af337af778/Management-of-type-2-diabetes-A-handbook-for-general-practice.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93887"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"461"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93887"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T09:47:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T09:47:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"461"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111817"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","na